The following passage describes a runtime weight precision swap mechanism for on-device large language model inference. Read it carefully and continue the explanation. The key insight is that during a precision swap, weights of individual layers are replaced atomically while decoding continues, and the choice of how many layers to swap per decode step controls the latency profile observed by the user. Specifically, swapping fewer or more than one layer at a time can result in much higher latency compared to using two consecutive swaps. The mechanism is illustrated below with an example where we perform 1x2 weight swap for inference.
